      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interest on your student loan is likely calculated using the daily balance method, which is a type of declining balance method. This means that the interest is calculated on the average daily balance of your loan, rather than the outstanding principal balance. The interest is then added to the principal, and the new balance is used to calculate the next month's interest. This process can create a snowball effect, where the interest seems to be growing faster than the principal, even if you're making the same monthly payments. As a result, it may take longer to pay off the loan than you expect.",
